segments.text: I would like to begin this interview by saying that my name is Charles Weiss and that I am interviewing my grandfather, Mr. John Addicks, who is currently living in the Salem community, which is located on Route 3, Brenham, Texas.
This interview is being conducted at his home on July 30, 1976, and the time is 7.45 p.m.
Okay, Grandpa, are you ready?
Yes.
Okay.
First, I'd like you to give me a little information as to where you were born, in what, and in what year.
I was born on August the 22nd, 1891, at Warrington, Fett County, Texas.
Were you born in your house?
And if so, did the doctor come to your house?
Yes.
He did come to your house?
Yes.
Okay.
Just how long ago did your family come to that area?
I'm referring to your mom and dad.
It must have been about ten years or so.
I see.
Do you know why they decided to come to that area?
Times were too difficult in Germany.
Oh, I see.
They were from Germany then.
Yes.
I see.
Are there a lot of German people in that area?
Yes, nothing but Germans.
Oh, I see.
Do you have any brothers or sisters?
I have no brother, but I have one sister.
She's dead, too.
I see.
Did you start school in Warrington or in Round Top?
I started school at Rocky Hill, Texas.
Rocky Hill, Texas.
Just where is that?
Oh, that's the country school right close to Warrington.
Okay.
Just how did you get to school?
Walked it.
How far did you live from the schoolhouse?
Oh, I guess about a mile and a half, two miles.
Did you have any other means of transportation, such as when it was raining or anything of that sort?
No, we had to walk.
I see.
Can you tell me something about the schoolhouse, such as was it a one-room schoolhouse, or how many teachers were there?
Something to do with that line.
It was a one-room schoolhouse, wooden, not sealed.
Taught, I believe, four readers, not grades at that time.
Four readers?
Yes.
What do you mean exactly by readers?
Well, readers, we call it grades now.
In those days, we called those
Readers.
First reader, second reader, third reader, fourth reader.
So in a sense there was one teacher to four readers.
Yeah.
I see.
Back then, what kind of activities did you do in your leisure time, such as when you were young?
What kind of activities did you do?
Like now we go out for ball games, to see ball games, to watch football games.
We have TV now, which you didn't have back then.
Just what exactly did y'all do?
Oh, chiefly hunting.
Uh-huh.
And not too often either.
Uh-huh.
Fishing once in a while.
I see.
What about maybe something like picnics on Sundays and things of that nature?
We didn't have any picnics.
I see.
What did y'all do on holidays, such as Easter and Thanksgiving, Christmas, Fourth of July?
We didn't do anything.
Sometimes we worked.
I see.
Did you have any...
Well, whatever celebrations you had, it was carried on in the house.
That's right.
I see.
Back then, do you remember any fads or any fashions that were kind of popular for that time?
The boys had to wear knee pants.
Anything else, I don't know.
Okay.
How about dances?
Were they popular back then?
That's the only entertainment we had.
I see.
Dances.
Okay.
Could you tell me a little bit about the first job you had and maybe what kind of pay that it had?
The first job was teaching at Wellcome.
Wellcome of Austin County.
I received $45 a month and had to pay $15 for a board.
So I had $30 left.
That's not very much now compared to what we have now.
I forgot to ask you back, where did you graduate from school to get your teaching degree?
I got my certificate at Blaine College for taking the examination, the state examination.
That was in 1960, I think, on April 8th and 9th, if I remember right, in 1916.
1916, I see.
Just how long were you a teacher in the public schools?
At that place?
One year only.
Then I was drafted to the United States Army, Army of Occupation.
How many years did you serve in the Army?
I served about 22 months.
You went overseas?
Yes, sir.
I see.
Spent about one month, I mean about one year overseas.
Uh-huh.
When you came back from the Army, did you take up teaching again?
Yes, sir.
And you taught where?
I taught at Salem, Washington County.
For how many years?
I taught 44 years.
I see.
44 years.
Then I got two years credit for military service.
Makes 46 years.
That's a long time.
Just when did you get married?
That was 1922.
Okay.
Got married.
And just where was she from?
From Wonder Hill, Washington County.
Small community.
I see.
And just what exactly was your reason for moving here?
The teaching job?
What was your reason for moving to where you presently are staying now?
Was it your job?
It was the biggest school.
I see.
And I had the principal's job over here.
Oh.
Just what kind of work did your... You said you had a sister.
Just what kind of work did she do, or where did she move to when she was married?
She stayed...
at Warrington, Texas all of my life.
Farmer's wife.
Okay.
What other kind of work did you do besides teaching?
Did you raise cattle or what other kind of farm?
I raised some cattle.
Did you raise anything like cotton or corn?
Yes.
I think all my life I raised one bale of cotton.
I see.
Just how big was your farm?
We had 150 acres at last.
I see.
But now we have 72 acres left.
Did you grow most of what you needed or did you buy quite a bit from town?
I think we bought quite a number of things from town.
Tell me something about the Depression.
How did it affect you and others around you?
Depression started in 1929.
We thought it would be over in just a few months, but it lasted a long time.
I think it wasn't over in 1939.
Did you feel any real hard effects from it, such as where youI don't know how to say itdid you feel that there was a shortage of food or a shortage of a lot of things around here?
Well, not exactly around here.
You see, we lived on the farm, and we didn't notice it so much.
But in larger cities, they had quite a bit of trouble.
I see.

Since you mentioned that you were a teacher, how do you think that the conditions have changed since the time that you've gone to school or since the time that you were teaching school, more so than the size of the school?
Maybe tell me a little bit about how you think maybe the... Well, in 1939,
I think it was in 1930, no, 1919, when I started teaching, we had 39 common school districts in the county.
Now we have two school districts left, and both were independent school districts.
They all have been consolidated.
Uh-huh.
When you taught school, how many teachers were teaching in that particular country school, and how many grades did each one teach?
We had Salem and Pleasant Hill, we had four.
We started out with two, and later on we increased it to four.
Four teachers?
Yes, four teachers.
I see.
And each one had how many grades?
They taught maybe two grades for each teacher on the hour?
Yes.
First we had to teach four grades, and then later on taught under two grades.
I see.
I remember having to go to...
when we went out from Pleasant Hill the last few years that it operated, and I think I had, was note, remembered that it was two grades to each teacher, mainly also.
Do you travel very much, or did you used to travel very much?
No, not so much, not anyhow.
Maybe to other towns when you did, nearby towns?
Yes, we did that all right.
Go to neighboring towns.
For maybe just to visit?
Yes, just to visit.
I see.
I guess Houston has always been a pretty big town around here.
Yes.
Have you ever been out of Texas besides for the war?
And for what reason did you go?
No, sir.
Never was out of Texas.
I always stayed in Texas.
That's Shreveport.
It was just a little bit, too.
Do you have any children?
Yeah, two.
Two?
Could you tell me where they have moved to and what's the type of work that they are doing now?
Well, we have a boy and a girl.
And a girl works in a tax office.
Uh-huh.
Here in Brenham?
Yes.
And the boy works in Houston as a certified public accountant.
They were raised up here in this area right here?
Yes, they were raised here.
Okay.
Backing up to what we were talking about, the war and its effect,
on the United States.
Do you recall anything that people usually tried to do to contribute to the war effort?
Like I know of in larger cities or so that they went to the factories and helped increase factories.
Well, they bought war bonds.
War bonds?
Yes.
Could you tell me a little bit about these war bonds?
Why they were created?
What way they helped?
That's directly to the government.
The government needed money, and they gave them the bonds for it.
Do you have any war bonds with you?
No, we don't have any left.
But you did have some?
Yes.
When you bought these bonds for a certain amount of money, they reimbursed you the same amount of money?
Yes.
Do you recall anything unusual about any of the presidential campaigns or elections besides the ones we've had here recently, such as the Watergate scandal and...
Anything to that nature?
No, I don't remember anything in particular.
Except President Wilson made a promise that I'd keep you out of the war, World War I.
Just as soon as he was elected, he was for it.
I see.
Do you remember any particular disasters or floods or tornadoes that's happened in this area or any surrounding area?
Well, we had a storm at Galveston.
We had a hailstorm in 1950.
It was in 1960, 1950.
They were pretty bad.
Do you remember a lot about Galveston, the storm there in, you said 1900?
Yes.
It killed about 6,000 people, I think.
I see.
This hail storm that you mentioned in 1950, just exactly what it was, that was just a little bit before my time.
Did that happen in this area?
That happened exactly in our community.
We had to put a new roof on our house.
I see.
It must have been pretty bad then.
Do you remember a lot about Hurricane Carla?
I know that was in 1962, I guess, somewhere back then.
I remember a little bit about that.
I guess that's no comparison to the other two.
No.
Do you ever remember having any problems among students in class?
I mean, in controlling them or anything related to that idea?
Never.
Problems.
However, we had them off and on, though, especially when the parents took up for the children.
I see.
Can you tell me something about integration?
When did it come in, and what promoted it to come in?
Well, it was brought on by the federal government.
We were forced to integrate.
That happened here about seven, eight years ago, I think.
You never witnessed any of it when you were teaching then?
No, sir.
That was after my time.
Uh-huh.
Do you remember any type of racial problems?
Did we have any racial problems in this area, do you think?
The integration first came in.
I don't think we did.
There was hardly any opposition then to it.
No.
I think that took place when I was about in the sixth grade, and it really didn't take over until when I was a freshman, I believe.
So I never witnessed anything either.
Just what type of people are living in this area now?
I mean, are they of German descent or any other type of... Chief of German descent.
Uh-huh.
And what type of work do they do?
Are there large farms or do they have other type of jobs?
Well, in 1919, all of the people worked on the farms to raise corn and cotton.
No one had jobs in town, but now everyone has a job in town.
Not only one, but the whole family.
And no cutting is raised anymore, and no corn.
That's changed entirely.
Then mostly the type of farms that are around here are for cattle raising?
Yes, cattle raising.
Just what kind of technological changes have you seen in farming in the last few years or in the last decade or so?
I don't know.
I've seen too many.
I mean, back when you raised cotton and everything, pretty well everything was done by...
Walking cultivators.
Now they have tractors.
Everyone has tractors on the farm.
Have you noticed anything else significantly besides that there are no crops being raised anymore and types of equipment?
No, not exactly.
People can't afford to own land anymore.
It's too expensive.
Do you think a lot of people are doing this cattle raising as a side business, that they have other jobs connected with it, or do you think that it's mainly their one occupation in this area?
It's not their chief occupation.
They do that besides the jobs they have in town.
Do you think that this area is getting larger?
And what I'm referring to in this area is Brenham.
Have you noticed a great change in size in the last few years?
Yes, I think so.
It's getting larger.
Just what type of...
Do you think businesses account for this growth, or just what exactly do you think is a major cause for all these people coming here and staying more now so than what they did before?
I think they have more factories in Brenham.
Such as?
Cotton factory, mattress factory.
And there are quite a number of others.
These weren't here 20 years ago?
The cotton factory was here a long time ago.
But as far as Sealy Mattress, they haven't been here as long.
No.
I see.
Just what type of changes have you noticed in the landscape?
like roads and buildings.
Have you noticed quite a bit of changing taking place in this area?
Well, out of the country, we haven't made many changes.
We still have dirt roads.
I guess you've seen a lot of changes on the highways.
Oh yes, the highways are fixed up.
Were there any major highways?
say 25 years ago around here?
25, I believe the first one was the highway that runs from Burton to Chapel Hill.
That was the first highway built in the county.
But I don't know exactly when it was built.
And later on Highway 36.
Then it made Fountain Market Roads.
They weren't made before the highways then.
They were put in... No, a little bit later on.
I see.
Do you notice any real big changes in the way kids are raised now as compared to when they were young?
Or maybe to the way you raised your children?
Oh yes, quite a bit of difference.
In what way?
They sent them to school much longer nowadays.
They had to go nine months.
In those days, some went six months, some seven, and then they had to stay at home and work on the farms.
So they were let out then early in spring.
That's right.
I guess you notice there's a lot of difference in the way they go to school now also.
Oh yes, that's right.
Pretty well, everyone walked to school.
In those days, everybody had to walk.
I imagine when you were young that, well,
What you listened to mainly was programs on the radio.
Do you remember any special programs back then that you always listened to?
I don't think we had any radios.
I don't think I remember that we had any.
When do you think they first came?
Radios came later on first.
Do you have any particular idea that you can...
as to what date that you can associate with it, maybe, that you first noticed?
We didn't have anything to listen to.
Uh-huh.
And radios haven't been here no more than about 30 or 40 years.
Yeah, that's right.
How long was it before you got your first TV?
Do you remember?
Oh, that's...
Pretty good while ago, I know.
Say maybe 20 years or 30 years?
I believe every bit of it, if not longer.
Did many people have one when they first came out, or was it just the wealthier people that had them that was more available?
I guess the wealthier were the first ones to get some, but after a while all the people bought them.
